One of the major problems in rapidtide is the "poison regressor problem" - if the initial regressor (usually constructed from the mean signal of the whole brain) contains data from multiple, distinct pools of voxels with different delays (rather than a relatively tight distribution with a strong central tendency), the initial global regressor will consist of multiple, delayed copies of the same underlying signal, much like echoes, except that in some cases, the echoes may precede the strongest signal in time.  As a result, the regressor is strongly autocorrelated, and delay fits become ambiguous.  This cannot be corrected by refinement, since the fits will have multiple, apparently valid delays to choose from, and this will persist even after refinement.  There are two ways to approach fixing this.  The first is to be extremely selective producing the initial regressor.  I added a feature a few years ago, ``--globalmeanselect``, to try to locate a good, uniform, short delay pool of voxels to use for the initial global mean signal.  This option selected only voxels with clear, short delays, after a single pass with despeckling disabled.  The result was a mask that could be used with ``--globalmeanincludemask`` for a subsequent run.   The implementation was not optimal, and employing it required running rapidtide multiple times.  It would be better if this were done in a preparation pass.  The second way to deal with this is to examine the regressor and try to sharpen it after the fact by detecting autocorrelations (both forward and backwards in time) and removing the delayed versions of the driving signal from the regressor in an analog of echo cancellation, or perhaps deconvolution.  There is an echocancel routine in rapidtide to do this, but it doesn't seem to work very well.  I would like to add the ability to rapidtide do both of these operations, either separately or in combination.
